Execution Layer

Overview

The Execution Layer is responsible for transforming treasury recommendations into executable transaction plans.

Rather than making autonomous decisions, this module validates proposed actions, simulates execution outcomes, estimates costs, and prepares transactions for approval.

The Execution Layer acts as the bridge between the Portfolio Manager and blockchain infrastructure while enforcing governance, security, and treasury policies.

Objectives

The Execution Layer aims to:

Prepare execution plans
Simulate treasury operations
Estimate execution costs
Optimize transaction routing
Validate treasury policies
Support multisig approval workflows
Prevent unauthorized execution
Maintain complete execution audit trails
Core Responsibilities
Transaction Planning

The Execution Layer converts AI recommendations into structured execution plans.

Supported operations include:

Portfolio rebalancing
Token swaps
Cross-chain transfers
Stablecoin allocation
Treasury funding
Liquidity deployment
Yield allocation
Execution Simulation

Every proposed action is simulated before approval.

Simulation includes:

Expected portfolio allocation
Estimated transaction costs
Price impact
Slippage
Gas consumption
Final portfolio composition

Example:

{
  "simulation": {
    "action": "rebalance",
    "estimated_gas_usd": 18.45,
    "estimated_slippage": 0.22,
    "expected_portfolio_value": 2861500
  }
}
Transaction Validation

Before an execution plan is approved, the module verifies:

Treasury policy compliance
Risk limits
Available balances
Supported assets
Approved counterparties
Chain compatibility
Liquidity availability

If validation fails, execution is blocked and an explanation is generated.

Routing Optimization

When multiple execution paths exist, the module selects the most efficient route.

Optimization criteria may include:

Lowest gas cost
Lowest slippage
Highest liquidity
Fastest settlement
Approved bridge providers
Preferred DEXs
Approval Workflow

The Execution Layer supports governance-first execution.

Typical workflow:

Portfolio Manager generates a recommendation.
Execution Layer validates the proposal.
Simulation results are generated.
Human reviewers inspect the proposal.
Multisig approval is collected.
Transaction is signed.
Transaction is broadcast.
Execution status is monitored.
